: Congress leader A.C. Jose who died in Kochi on Saturday will be remembered for his contribution to the trade union movement, giving leadership to as many as 80 unions affiliated to the Indian National Trade Union Congress (INTUC) cutting across industrial sectors.He made his entry into politics through the students movement, becoming the second president of the Kerala Students Union (KSU). He made his Assembly debut in 1980, by winning the North Paravur seat. He gained notoriety for using his casting vote as Speaker during a four-month term in the chair to save the K. Karunakaran governmentâ€™s downfall in 1982.Born on February 5, 1937, Mr. Jose was loyal to the Antony faction in the Congress. He was an MP for three terms, representing different constituencies on each occasion. He won from Idukki in 1996, Mukundapuram in 1998, and Thrissur in 1999.Chief Minister Oommen Chandy recalled that his pleasant friendship with Mr. Jose began during his KSU days and lasted life long. Home Minister Ramesh Chennithala recalled his contributions towards the trade union movement. CPI State secretary Kanam Rajendran, CPI leader C. Divakaran, Speaker N. Sakthan, Deputy Speaker Palode Ravi, Revenue Minister Adoor Prakash, Forest Minister Thiruvanchoor Radhakrishnan, Electricity Minister Aryadan Mohammed, Water Resources Minister P.J. Joseph, and Scheduled Tribes Welfare Minister P.K. Jayalakshmi condoled the death.